content.description:
This is route number 38 in the 3rd Edition of Swartling's and Mayer's guide. 

  "Face opposite small tower.  Start on left side of face, then angle up and right to small inside corner.  Climb to upper ledge, then up crack or right corner to top."
content.protection: Nuts and small cams.  There is no protection for the last ~10 feet, and a leader faces a ledge fall here.
content.location: There is an obvious pit/cave at the bottom of this route, to the climbers right.  The 5.8 variation to this route, "Hissing Vulture", starts in the bottom of this pit.  Follow the northeast trail from Misery Gully, if coming down from the Frigate.  Or head up the southwest trail leading from Porkchop Buttress.

content.description: Climb the left corner of the Dungeon Wall. This is a named route in Knower and #35 in Swartling/Mayer.
content.location: The route runs up the left hand corner of the Dungeon Wall. You could start climbing the corner at the same level as Iron Maiden but to actually start at the bottom of the left corner you need to walk left and down from the Iron Maiden level.

content.description: This route starts just 3 feet right of dungeon wall crack.If follows the Knife arete corner of the wall.Stay on or near corner.This route is very sharp,be careful the crux is where the name is from.
content.protection: a couple pieces of 20 foot webbing and a small selection of gear should be good enough.cams,nuts,small hex's

content.description: this route is number 38 in your guide book.when we first did this route,my buddy rappelled down,and heard a loud hissing noise coming from the cave right below the climb,turns out it was a injured turkey vulture trying to scare us away.Start right under the overhang and continue up the crack to top.
content.protection: Tricky lead,butt possible maybe small to medium stoppers,and cams.Top rope use cord or webbing to 25 feet or three small pieces of webbing.small and medium cams or hexs.picture perfect top rope setup.

content.description: Climb lower face 5 ft. left of Dungeon Wall Crack.   Listed as a "variation" in the Swartling Guide.  It is such a nice moderate route I thought it deserved a name.   Gave it a 5.7+ as it is harder than DWC.
Climb thin crack 5 feet left of corner.  Half way up there is a crack that is always damp or wet.  Oh and it's a hold.  Have fun!
content.protection: Can be easily toproped.  Bring some webbing and cams or nuts.  Not sure on lead.

content.description: Easy climbing up a broken chimney. This is a named climb in Swartling/Mayer and is not listed in Knower.
content.location: Walk left around the corner from the main Dungeon Wall and you'll see an an obvious blocky chimney.

content.description: Climb the Wide crack using some face holds.  The crux  is climbing through the widest part of the crack. Crack ends at a ledge, follow easy ground to the top.  This route could only be made better if the crack was longer. Eliminating face holds would increase the difficulty considerably.
content.protection: .75 to #5 sized cams and a couple of nuts near the top.  You can belay off a tree.
content.location: This route is located near the corner about 30 feet up hill from the Pork Loin Variation crack.  I think it is route 44 in the Swartling and Meyer's guide. According to the guide this is part of Dungeon Wall however it is much closer to Porkchop.

pathTokens: West Bluff 02 - Misery Rocks & The Pantry

content.description:
The Dungeon Wall is located just southeast of the Frigate.  The routes here are mostly toperope,with 6+ climbs.  It's in the shade most of the day, with easy rap, and downclimb access. 

  Dungeon Wall Crack is a 5.6 in the middle of the rock.  There is a drainage crack, so this climb is always wet.  Makes it fun.
